1756	\begin{proof}
1757	  \uses{def:gr_glued_scheme, def:gr_transition}
1758	  The products \(U^I \times_{\mathbb{Z}} U^J\), as \(I, J\) range over the
1759	  size-\(d\) subsets, form an affine open cover of \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)
1760	  \times_{\mathbb{Z}} \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\). Separatedness may be checked on this
1761	  cover: it suffices to show that for each pair \((I,J)\) the preimage
1762	  \(\Delta^{-1}(U^I \times_{\mathbb{Z}} U^J)\) maps by a closed immersion into
1763	  \(U^I \times_{\mathbb{Z}} U^J\), i.e.\ that the corresponding ring
1764	  homomorphism is surjective.
1765	
1766	  By \cref{def:gr_glued_scheme} the diagonal preimage is the overlap
1767	  \(\Delta^{-1}(U^I \times_{\mathbb{Z}} U^J) = U^I \cap U^J = U^I_J = \Spec
1768	  \mathbb{Z}[X^I, 1/P^I_J]\). The restricted diagonal corresponds to the ring map
1769	  \[
1770	    \delta_{I,J} : \mathbb{Z}[X^I] \otimes_{\mathbb{Z}} \mathbb{Z}[X^J]
1771	    \longrightarrow \mathbb{Z}[X^I, 1/P^I_J],
1772	    \qquad
1773	    X^I \otimes 1 \mapsto X^I, \quad 1 \otimes X^J \mapsto (X^I_J)^{-1} X^I,
1774	  \]
1775	  the second component being the comorphism \(\theta_{I,J}\) of
1776	  \cref{def:gr_transition} (a point of \(U^I_J\) and its image under
1777	  \(\theta_{I,J}\) are the two coordinates of a point of the diagonal). We claim
1778	  \(\delta_{I,J}\) is surjective. Its image contains all entries of \(X^I\)
1779	  (from the first factor). From the second factor it contains the entries of
1780	  \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\); taking the \(I\)-minor of this matrix, and using
1781	  \(X^I_I = 1_{d\times d}\), the image contains the entries of \((X^I_J)^{-1}\),
1782	  and in particular
1783	  \[
1784	    \delta_{I,J}(1 \otimes P^J_I) = \det\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1}\bigr) = 1/P^I_J .
1785	  \]
1786	  Hence \(1/P^I_J\) lies in the image, so the image is all of
1787	  \(\mathbb{Z}[X^I, 1/P^I_J]\) and \(\delta_{I,J}\) is surjective. Concretely the
1788	  closed subscheme \(\Delta_{I,J} \subseteq U^I \times_{\mathbb{Z}} U^J\) is cut
1789	  out by the entries of the matrix relation
1790	  \[
1791	    X^J_I \, X^I - X^J \;=\; 0,
1792	  \]
1793	  which on the diagonal holds because \(X^J = (X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\) forces
1794	  \(X^J_I = (X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_I = (X^I_J)^{-1}\) and therefore \(X^J_I X^I =
1795	  (X^I_J)^{-1} X^I = X^J\). As each restricted diagonal is a closed immersion,
1796	  \(\Delta\) is a closed immersion and \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) is separated over
1797	  \(\mathbb{Z}\).
1798	\end{proof}
