1862	\begin{proof}
1863	  \uses{def:gr_glued_scheme, lem:gr_separated, def:gr_transition}
1864	  Since \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is of finite type
1865	  (\cref{def:gr_glued_scheme}) and separated (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), and
1866	  \(\mathbb{Z}\) is Noetherian, properness follows from the valuative criterion
1867	  for discrete valuation rings: it suffices to show that every solid diagram
1868	  \[
1869	    \begin{array}{ccc}
1870	      \Spec K & \xrightarrow{\ \varphi\ } & \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \\
1871	      \downarrow & & \downarrow \pi \\
1872	      \Spec R & \longrightarrow & \Spec \mathbb{Z}
1873	    \end{array}
1874	  \]
1875	  with \(R\) a discrete valuation ring, \(K = \operatorname{Frac}(R)\) and
1876	  valuation \(\nu : K \to \mathbb{Z} \cup \{\infty\}\), admits a unique diagonal
1877	  filler \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\).
1878	
1879	  \emph{Existence.} The morphism \(\varphi : \Spec K \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) lands
1880	  in some chart \(U^I\) (\(\Spec K\) has one point), so it is given by a ring map
1881	  \(f : \mathbb{Z}[X^I] \to K\). Among the \(\binom{r}{d}\) minors choose \(J\)
1882	  with \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\) minimal. Because \(P^I_I = 1\) gives \(f(P^I_I) = 1\)
1883	  with \(\nu = 0\), the minimum satisfies \(\nu(f(P^I_J)) \le 0\); in particular
1884	  \(f(P^I_J) \ne 0\), so \(f(X^I_J) \in \mathrm{GL}_d(K)\) is invertible over
1885	  \(K\). Define
1886	  \[
1887	    g : \mathbb{Z}[X^J] \longrightarrow K, \qquad
1888	    g(X^J) = f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\bigr) ;
1889	  \]
1890	  this is the composite of \(\theta_{I,J}\) (\cref{def:gr_transition}) with
1891	  \(f\), so \(g\) defines the same \(K\)-point \(\varphi\), now exhibited as
1892	  landing in \(U^J\).
1893	
1894	  We show every entry \(g(x^J_{p,q})\) lies in \(R\), i.e.\ has \(\nu \ge 0\).
1895	  First, for any size-\(d\) subset \(K' \subseteq \{1,\dots,r\}\) the \(K'\)-minor
1896	  of \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\) is \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\), so
1897	  \[
1898	    g(P^J_{K'}) = \det f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\bigr)
1899	    = \frac{f(P^I_{K'})}{f(P^I_J)},
1900	    \qquad
1901	    \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) = \nu(f(P^I_{K'})) - \nu(f(P^I_J)) \ge 0
1902	  \]
1903	  by minimality of \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\). Now the \(J\)-minor \(X^J_J\) of \(X^J\) is
1904	  the identity, so by cofactor expansion each individual entry
1905	  \(x^J_{p,q}\) (with \(q \notin J\)) equals, up to sign, the minor
1906	  \(P^J_{K'}\) for \(K' = (J \setminus \{j_p\}) \cup \{q\}\) -- the \(d \times d\)
1907	  determinant obtained by replacing the \(p\)-th identity column of \(X^J_J\) by
1908	  the column \(q\). Hence \(\nu(g(x^J_{p,q})) = \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) \ge 0\) for all
1909	  entries, and the entries with \(q \in J\) are \(0\) or \(1\). Therefore
1910	  \(g(\mathbb{Z}[X^J]) \subseteq R\), so \(g\) factors uniquely as
1911	  \(\mathbb{Z}[X^J] \to R \hookrightarrow K\). The corresponding morphism
1912	  \(\Spec R \to U^J \hookrightarrow \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) restricts to \(\varphi\)
1913	  over \(\Spec K\) and lies over \(\Spec \mathbb{Z}\), providing the filler.
1914	
1915	  \emph{Uniqueness.} Any two fillers agree over the generic point \(\Spec K\)
1916	  and, \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) being separated over \(\mathbb{Z}\)
1917	  (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), two morphisms \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\)
1918	  agreeing on the schematically dense open \(\Spec K\) coincide. This verifies
1919	  the valuative criterion, so \(\pi : \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is
1920	  proper.
1921	\end{proof}
